frameDefinitions: An Agent performs a Response action in consequence of a Trigger event.
The words in this frame describe an Experiencer's feelings of tolerating with respect to some Content.
The words in this frame describe an Experiencer's emotions with respect to some Content.
In this frame an Experiencer experiences an Emotion or is in an Emotional_state.
This frames describes a Perceiver who fails to keep sight of a Theme.
A Protagonist has (or does not have) a Weapon.
frameExamples: I <t>respond</t> to earthquakes by hiding under my desk.
He could not <t>tolerate</t> the smell of coconut .
My <t>enjoyment</t> of the movie was considerably impaired by the seven-foot guy sitting in front of me.
The police <t>lost</t> the burglar as the thief turned the corner.
Apparently, the suspect is <t>armed</t> with a shotgun.
listRoleDefinitions: The means action whereby the <fen>Agent</fen> responds to the Trigger.
A non-agentive entity that is impinged upon by a <fen>Trigger</fen> event to which they respond.
An event that impinges upon the <fen>Agent</fen> or <fen>Responding_entity</fen> and produces a <fen>Response</fen> from it.
The intentional <fen>Agent</fen> that is impinged upon by a <fen>Trigger</fen> event to which they respond.
The point in time when the <fen>Agent</fen> or <fen>Responding_entity</fen> manifests its <fen>Response</fen> to the <fen>Trigger</fen> .
The location in which the <fen>Response</fen> action takes place.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences tolerance with respect to the <fen>Content</fen>.

<fen>Content</fen> is what the <fen>Experiencer</fen>'s feeling of tolerance is directed towards..  The <fen>Content</fen> differs from a stimulus because the <fen>Content</fen> is not construed as being direcly responsible for causing the emotion.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the area about which the <fen>Experiencer</fen> has the  tolerated experience(s).
The <fen>State</fen> is the abstract noun that describes a more lasting experience by the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The <fen>Event</fen> is the occasion or happening that <fen>Experiencer</fen>s in a certain emotional state participate in.
The time at which the <fen>Experiencer</fen> is in the state of toleration.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences the emotion or other internal state.

<fen>Content</fen> is what the <fen>Experiencer</fen>'s feelings or experiences are directed towards or based upon.  The <fen>Content</fen> differs from a stimulus because the <fen>Content</fen> is not construed as being direcly responsible for causing the emotion.

The Frame Element <fen>Expressor</fen> marks expressions that indicate a body part, gesture or other expression of the <fen>Experiencer</fen> that reflect his or her emotional state.  They describe a presentation of the experience or emotion denoted by the adjective or noun.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the area about which the <fen>Experiencer</fen> has the particular experience.
The <fen>State</fen> is the abstract noun that describes a more lasting experience by the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The <fen>Event</fen> is the occasion or happening that <fen>Experiencer</fen>s in a certain emotional state participate in.
The time at which the <fen>Experiencer</fen> is in the specified emotional state.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences the <fen>Emotion</fen> or is in the <fen>Emotional_state</fen>.
The <fen>Emotion</fen> is the feeling that the <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences.
The <fen>Emotional_state</fen> is the state the <fen>Experiencer</fen> is in.
The <fen>Evaluation</fen> is a negative or positive assessment of the <fen>Experiencer</fen> regarding his or her <fen>Emotional_state</fen>.
The <fen>Perceiver</fen> is the entity who fails to keep the <fen>Theme</fen> in sight.
The <fen>Theme</fen> is the object that becomes unperceivable.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Perceiver</fen> loses perception of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Perceiver</fen> loses perception of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The destructive device that the <fen>Protagonist</fen> has with them.
The individual that possesses a <fen>Weapon</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Protagonist</fen> carries a <fen>Weapon</fen>.
The location where a <fen>Protagonist</fen> carries a <fen>Weapon</fen>.
